weewx-tigo
Copyright 2025 Matthew Wall
Distributed under terms of the GPLv3

This is a driver for weewx that captures data from TIGO solar panel monitors.

Note that there will be no output from the TIGO when there is no sunlight on
the panels.  You might be confused when you try to install/configure the driver
at night, but it is only because the panels only output data when they are
illuminated.


===============================================================================
Installation

0) install pre-requisites

  a) install weewx
      http://weewx.com/docs
  b) install taptap and verify functionality
      https://github.com/willglynn/taptap

1) install the driver

weectl extension install https://github.com/matthewwall/weewx-tigo/archive/master.zip

2) run the driver directly to verify functionality

export WEEWX_BINDIR=/usr/share/weewx
export WEEWX_USRDIR=/etc/weewx/bin/user
PYTHONPATH=$WEEWX_BINDIR python3 $WEEWX_USRDIR/tigo.py

3) configure the driver

weectl station reconfigure --driver=user.tigo

4) start weewx

sudo systemctl start weewx


===============================================================================
panel support

The driver supports up to 50 solar panels.  If you have more than 50 panels
connected to the TIGO, modify MAX_PANELS in tigo.py before the database is
created (which happens the first time you run weewx with the tigo schema).


===============================================================================
panel map

Each solar panel is identified by a combination of gateway and node IDs.  These
must be mapped to the generic field names of p1, p2, p3, ... in the database.
The panel_map section of the configuration file defines this mapping.

To find the identifiers, run the driver directly with the list-identifiers
action:

  tigo.py --action list-identifiers

Using the resulting list, create the panel_map section in the TIGO section of
the weewx configuration file.

For example,

$ PYTHONPATH=$WEEWX_BINDIR python3 $WEEWX_USRDIR/tigo.py --action list-identifiers
listening for 30 seconds
found 3 unique identifiers
  4609.10
  4609.11
  4609.12

This becomes:

[TIGO]
  driver = user.tigo
  [[panel_map]]
    p1 = 4609.10
    p2 = 4609.11
    p3 = 4609.12


===============================================================================
taptap

Taptap is a rust application that listens for and decodes the TIGO protocol
from a Cloud Connect Advanced (CCA) device.  This requires an RS485 device,
either serial, serial-to-usb, or serial-to-tcp, that is wired to the 'gateway'
ground, A, and B wires of the CCA and acts as a 'tap' - a read-only monitor of
the RS485 communication between the CCA and the TIGO solar panel monitor(s).

The taptap README has the wiring details and guidance:

  https://github.com/willglynn/taptap

The TIGO web site shows the actual CCA device and status information:

  https://support.tigoenergy.com/hc/en-us/articles/224215048-Cloud-Connect-Advanced-CCA-LED-status-information

To build taptap, you need a rust development environment.  You might be able to
use the rust package for your operating system, but it might be safer to use
the latest rust.  For details see https://rust-lang.org/tools/install/

  curl --proto '=https' --tlsv1.2 -sSf https://sh.rustup.rs | sh

The taptap application needs libudev:

  sudo apt install libudev-dev

Then you can build and install taptap something like this:

  git clone https://github.com/willglynn/taptap
  cd taptap
  cargo build
  cargo install --path . --root /opt/taptap

Now you can verify that taptap works:

  /opt/taptap/bin/taptap list-serial-ports

Collect data by specifying the serial port listed in the previous command:

  /opt/taptap/bin/taptap observe --serial /dev/ttyUSB0

This should result in JSON-formatted data:

{"gateway":{"id":4610},"node":{"id":37},"timestamp":"2025-10-08T10:38:01.942422696-04:00","voltage_in":31.7,"voltage_out":31.4,"current":0.645,"dc_dc_duty_cycle":1.0,"temperature":15.3,"rssi":126}
